data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 11, the **sync-over-async opt-in for the Cosmos DB provider is removed entirely**. The temporary compatibility shim you configured in .NET 10 no longer exists.

Every synchronous call — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, `SaveChanges()` — will throw an **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime with no workaround.

### The fix: migrate to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

### Key changes

| .NET 10 (with opt-in) | .NET 11 (required) |
|---|---|
| `ToList()` | `await ToListAsync()` |
| `First()` / `Single()` | `await FirstAsync()` / `await SingleAsync()` |
| `Count()` / `Any()` | `await CountAsync()` / `await AnyAsync()` |
| `SaveChanges()` | `await SaveChangesAsync()` |

### What to watch for

1. **Callers must go async too** — `async` propagates up the call stack, so controllers/services calling these methods need `async Task<IActionResult>` signatures, etc.
2. **`Add()` stays synchronous** — it only tracks the entity in the change tracker; no I/O happens until `SaveChangesAsync()`.
3. **`FirstAsync` vs `FirstOrDefaultAsync`** — same semantics as before; `FirstAsync` throws if no element is found.

The Cosmos SDK has always been async-only under the hood — EF Core 11 simply stops hiding that behind a sync wrapper.
